subSection.paragraph:
The structural diversity of compounds isolated from natural sources, together with the biological activity they present, is unquestionable. These metabolites have few rivals in any available synthetic screening library (
Butler, 2008
). It is well-documented that these privileged scaffolds serve as important platforms, as they are biologically pre-validated for library design in the search for new drug candidates (
DeCorte, 2016
; 
Rodrigues et al., 2016
).

Nowadays, natural products continue to have a great impact on human health. In addition, chemists have generated semisynthetic analogs that are often more successful than the original natural product in terms of clinical importance (
Davison and Brimble, 2019
; 
Newman and Cragg, 2020
).

In this sense, a large group of compounds of natural origin with a wide range of recognized biological activities is constituted by sesquiterpene lactones (SLs) (
Sülsen et al., 2018
). These represent one of the most relevant groups of metabolites isolated from the family 
Asteraceae
. Such C-15 terpenoidal compounds commonly have an α- methylene-γ- lactone group in their structure, which is considered essential for their activity (
Kimani et al., 2018a
, b). This chemical functionality is often responsible for biological effects and, in some cases, cytotoxic activity is attributed to this feature. Structural modifications in this group cause the loss of both cytotoxicity and tumor inhibition. Biological activity reports include anticancer, anti-inflammatory, and antiparasitic properties (
Jimenez et al., 2014
; 
Martino et al., 2015
; 
Muschietti and Ulloa, 2016
). Special mention should be made of anticancer agents, which have proved to have significant cytotoxic activity and selectivity against different tumor cell lines. This remarkable property of some of them and their semi-synthetic derivatives is currently being tested in clinical trials (
Caldwell and Yan, 2014
; 
Ghantous et al., 2010
).

In this sense, another important bioactivity reported for some pseudoguaianolide SL 
types
isolated from 

Ambrosia
spp. (Asteraceae)

is the trypanocidal activity and its mechanisms (
Sülsen et al., 2008
; 
Sülsen et al., 2011
; 
Sülsen et al., 2013
; 
Sülsen et al., 2016
; 
da Silva et al., 2013
).

American trypanosomiasis, known as Chagas disease, is caused by infection with the protozoan parasite 

Trypanosoma cruzi

. It is endemic to 21 Latin American countries (
World Health Organization, 2021
), and current treatments are based on benznidazole and nifurtimox, which are both effective, mainly in the acute phase of infection (P´erez-Molina and Molina, 2018). These drugs have severe side effects, and a low treatment adherence rate. In fact, they have been marketed for more than 50 years, are expensive, require long-term treatment, their efficacy to treat the chronic stage of the disease is still controversial, and can favor the development of drug-resistant parasites (
García et al., 2018
; 
Ribeiro et al., 2020
).

Since the 1990s, there has been a renewed interest in herbal medicine, and research on the antiprotozoal effects of plants has been conducted. Several studies of extracts of raw plants, fractions, and pure compounds have allowed the identification of potential treatments for Chagas disease, reducing parasitemia, and showing low cytotoxicity for mammalian cells (
Izumi et al., 2011
).

One feasible technique for obtaining diversity in natural products, as demonstrated in recent reports, is to strengthen nature’ s biosynthetic machinery. This goal is accomplished by chemically modifying vegetal extracts to produce a wide range of previously unknown semi-synthetic chemicals in a single step (Lopez´et al., 2007; 
Ramallo et al., 2018
).

The diversity of enhanced extracts is achieved through chemical modifications able to reshape the naturally occurring molecular scaffolds through a simple chemical reaction (
Tomohara et al., 2016
). As a result of the isolation of the modified compounds, natural product-like compounds with a dual outcome are obtained, on the one hand, for a strategy of expanding diversity and, on the other, for the fortuitous discovery of a natural product research (
Ramallo et al., 2011
).

Due to the chemical complexity of the extracts (non-modified or modified) and their intended therapeutic applications, the bioguided fractionation model can be applied. In this regard, bioguided assays with extracts can provide relevant information as a guide for determining how to intensify fractionations and purifications. Furthermore, the discovery of previously undescribed bioactive compounds is inherent to these 
types
of studies. These metabolites are found in less quantity and are less likely to be isolated in a traditional phytochemical study. Besides, useful synergy, addition, and, in some cases, antagonistic interactions are observed. As a result, the overall process is more productive because only the most biologically relevant fractions are explored further (Alvarez´Touron, 2018; 
Fadel et al., 2018
; 
Montes-Avila et al., 2017
).

The traditional phytochemical processing of the 

A. tenuifolia

extract resulted in previously reported different terpenoids (
Herz et al., 1969
; 
Montes-Avila et al., 2017
; 
Oberti et al., 1986
; 
Silva et al., 1992
). In this study, the main isolated compound was psilostachyin B (Psi B) (
Mabry et al., 1966
), in contrast to previous phytochemical studies in which psilostachyins A and C (Psi A and C) were the main isolated compounds (
Silva et al., 1992
). The structures of the isolated SLs (
Fig. 1
) were established based on their NMR data and by comparison with those previously reported (
Olivaro et al., 2016
), and the chemical structures of previously undescribed compounds were elucidated by a combination of 1- and 2-dimensional NMR experiments. The characterization of compounds was completed with other spectroscopic and spectropolarimetric methods (see experimental section).

The analysis of the compounds present in the plant extract revealed that the reactive points of derivatization are, in general, hydroxyls, carbonyls and olefins. If a modification of reactive centers is pursued, 
meta
-chloroperbenzoic acid (
m
CPBA) could be used as chemical reagent (
Kawamura et al., 2011
). This is a versatile and inexpensive oxidant, easy to handle and capable of oxidizing an assortment of functional groups under generally mild and clean conditions. It produces stereoselective olefin epoxidation reactions, heteroatom oxidation reactions, oxidative rearrangements and cleavages, Baeyer-Villiger oxidations, among others. There are reports in which transannulation reactions also occurred as a consequence of opening reactions of epoxy rings, contributing to the diversification of compounds (
Hussain et al., 2014
). In fact, epoxidation constitutes a new ring formation reaction, and this chemical functionality is an important heterocyclic unit found in various naturally occurring molecules. One may argue that oxirane rings are certainly electrophilic and reactive, which may be associated with possible toxicity, as exploited in antitumor cytotoxic agents. However, there are numerous reports of bioactive therapeutical compounds with more than one epoxide group in their structure (
Gomes et al., 2020
). They are even derivatized or loaded into nanocarriers to avoid their low bioavailability or aqueous solubility, but these groups, which are responsible for their biological activity, are retained (
Fidler et al., 2003
; 
Qiu and Kao, 2003
).

Epoxide-containing compounds, either naturally occurring or obtained by chemical modification, allowed arriving at a key structural motif regarding trypanocidal activity. As described in medicinal chemistry, a small structural change is capable of translating into an important change in biological activity (
Guo, 2017
). The configuration of the epoxy group (along with its intrinsic characteristic of being an electrophile capable of reacting with cellular nucleophiles as well as a hydrogen bond acceptor) proves to be a molecular determinant to increase parasite inhibition. To date, this is a novel finding that will serve as the foundation for future research aimed at the synthesis of more active and selective derivatives with less toxicity. Furthermore, it is the starting point for a mechanistic study of parasite growth inhibition at different stages, which may lead to finding the molecular target. This is still one of the biggest questions in this field of research and reaching consensus on it represents a difficult challenge.

Reagents used for derivatization were purchased in Sigma-Aldrich. Benznidazole (purity 99.2 ± 0.5% w/w) was extracted and purified from commercially available tablets (Radanil®, Roche, 
Argentina
), as reported in previous works (
García et al., 2016
).

